\f0\b\fs36 \cf2 GOD
\f1\b0\fs24 \
\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f0\b \cf2 \'a0
\f1\b0 In the days when the judges ruled,\'a0there was a famine in the land.\'a0So a man from Bethlehem in Judah,\'a0together with his wife and two sons, went to live for a while\'a0in the country of Moab.\'a0
\f0\b\fs20 \super 2\'a0
\f1\b0\fs24 \nosupersub The man\'92s name was Elimelek,\'a0his wife\'92s name was Naomi, and the names of his two sons were Mahlon and Kilion.\'a0They were Ephrathites\'a0from Bethlehem,\'a0Judah. And they went to Moab and lived there.\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f0\b\fs20 \cf2 \super 3\'a0
\f1\b0\fs24 \nosupersub Now Elimelek, Naomi\'92s husband, died, and she was left with her two sons.\'a0
\f0\b\fs20 \super 4\'a0
\f1\b0\fs24 \nosupersub They married Moabite women,\'a0one named Orpah and the other Ruth.\'a0After they had lived there about ten years,\'a0
\f0\b\fs20 \super 5\'a0
\f1\b0\fs24 \nosupersub both Mahlon and Kilion\'a0also died,\'a0and Naomi was left without her two sons and her husband.\
\pard\pardeftab720\sa280\partightenfactor0

\f0\b\fs28 \cf2 \uc0\u8232 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\fs20 \cf2 \super 6\'a0
\f1\b0\fs24 \nosupersub When Naomi heard in Moab\'a0that the\'a0Lord\'a0had come to the aid of his people\'a0by providing food\'a0for them, she and her daughters-in-law\'a0prepared to return home from there.\'a0
\f0\b\fs20 \super 7\'a0
\f1\b0\fs24 \nosupersub With her two daughters-in-law she left the place where she had been living and set out on the road that would take them back to the land of Judah.\

\f0\b\fs20 \super 8\'a0
\f1\b0\fs24 \nosupersub Then Naomi said to her two daughters-in-law, \'93Go back, each of you, to your mother\'92s home.\'a0May the\'a0Lord\'a0show you kindness,\'a0as you have shown kindness to your dead husbands\'a0and to me.\'a0
\f0\b\fs20 \super 9\'a0
\f1\b0\fs24 \nosupersub May the\'a0Lord\'a0grant that each of you will find rest\'a0in the home of another husband.\'94\
\
Then she kissed\'a0them goodbye and they wept aloud\'a0
\f0\b\fs20 \super 10\'a0
\f1\b0\fs24 \nosupersub and said to her, \'93We will go back with you to your people.\'94\

\f0\b\fs20 \super 11\'a0
\f1\b0\fs24 \nosupersub But Naomi said, \'93Return home, my daughters. Why would you come with me? Am I going to have any more sons, who could become your husbands?\'a0
\f0\b\fs20 \super 12\'a0
\f1\b0\fs24 \nosupersub Return home, my daughters; I am too old to have another husband. Even if I thought there was still hope for me\'97even if I had a husband tonight and then gave birth to sons\'97\'a0
\f0\b\fs20 \super 13\'a0
\f1\b0\fs24 \nosupersub would you wait until they grew up?\'a0Would you remain unmarried for them? No, my daughters. It is more bitter\'a0for me than for you, because the\'a0Lord\'92s hand has turned against me!\'94\

\f0\b\fs20 \super 14\'a0
\f1\b0\fs24 \nosupersub At this they wept\'a0aloud again. Then Orpah kissed her mother-in-law\'a0goodbye,\'a0but Ruth clung to her.\

\f0\b\fs20 \super 15\'a0
\f1\b0\fs24 \nosupersub \'93Look,\'94 said Naomi, \'93your sister-in-law\'a0is going back to her people and her gods.\'a0Go back with her.\'94\

\f0\b\fs20 \super 16\'a0
\f1\b0\fs24 \nosupersub But Ruth replied, \'93Don\'92t urge me to leave you\'a0or to turn back from you. Where you go I will go, and where you stay I will stay. Your people will be my people\'a0and your God my God.\'a0
\f0\b\fs20 \super 17\'a0
\f1\b0\fs24 \nosupersub Where you die I will die, and there I will be buried. May the\'a0Lord\'a0deal with me, be it ever so severely,\'a0if even death separates you and me.\'94\'a0
\f0\b\fs20 \super 18\'a0
\f1\b0\fs24 \nosupersub When Naomi realized that Ruth was determined to go with her, she stopped urging her.\

\f0\b\fs20 \super 19\'a0
\f1\b0\fs24 \nosupersub So the two women went on until they came to Bethlehem.\'a0When they arrived in Bethlehem, the whole town was stirred\'a0because of them, and the women exclaimed, \'93Can this be Naomi?\'94\

\f0\b\fs20 \super 20\'a0
\f1\b0\fs24 \nosupersub \'93Don\'92t call me Naomi,\'94 she told them. \'93Call me Mara,\'a0because the Almighty\'a0has made my life very bitter.\'a0
\f0\b\fs20 \super 21\'a0
\f1\b0\fs24 \nosupersub I went away full, but the\'a0Lord\'a0has brought me back empty.\'a0Why call me Naomi? The\'a0Lord\'a0has afflicted\'a0me;\'a0the Almighty has brought misfortune upon me.\'94\

\f0\b\fs20 \super 22\'a0
\f1\b0\fs24 \nosupersub So Naomi returned from Moab accompanied by Ruth the Moabite,\'a0her daughter-in-law,\'a0arriving in Bethlehem as the barley harvest\'a0was beginning.\
\
